{
  "text": "For such investigations, the PRE for 1 H-transverse magnetization (referred to here as 1 H-C 2 ) is often used. The large magnitude of 1 H-C 2 makes it a highly sensitive probe. This is due to the large nuclear gyromagnetic ratio of the proton and the primary dependence of 1 H-C 2 on the spectral density function at zero-frequency. In addition, 1 H-C 2 is much less susceptible to internal motions and cross relaxation than the longitudinal 1 H-PRE (referred to as 1 H-C 1 ) which is highly sensitive to these two factors [CITATION_1] . For quantitative analysis, it is very important to accurately and precisely measure 1 H-C 2 rates and to understand potential pitfalls in the measurements. In this paper, we describe practical aspects of 1 H-C 2 measurements for amide protons of proteins.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "25735670"
  },
